From 0330890223d46d89a0bbcf995f8cd30647277814 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Nadia Chambers <nadia.yvette.chambers@ik.me>
Date: Sun, 31 May 2026 07:36:27 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 130/174] mm: insert arch MMU cache for every sub-PTE installed
 by anon/COW clustering
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

PGCL's do_anonymous_page and wp_page_copy install one PTE per MMUPAGE in
the kernel page that holds the fault (PAGE_MMUCOUNT sub-PTEs total) but
only called update_mmu_cache_range() once, for the faulting sub-PTE.
The remaining sub-PTEs were valid in the page tables but absent from the
arch-private MMU cache (TSB on sparc64) — every userspace touch outside
the faulting sub-PAGE took a TLB miss and relied on the slow page-table
walker to refill.

On sparc64 PGCL=2 (PAGE_SIZE=32 KiB on 8 KiB MMUPAGEs, 4 sub-PTEs per
cluster) that walker path doesn't successfully complete the TLB fill —
the trap immediately re-fires on the next instruction and the user PC
gets pinned on the second-MMUPAGE access in an unbreakable kernel fault
loop.  Confirmed via QEMU monitor `info registers`: user PC stuck on the
faulting `stb`, kernel PC repeatedly inside handle_mm_fault, /dev/kmsg
shows the fault address +0x2000 (one MMUPAGE past the cluster base).

Pre-install the arch-MMU-cache entry alongside set_ptes for every
sub-PTE we write.  No-op for !PGCL (loop body runs once with nr=1).
update_mmu_cache_range on the other archs that have a real implementation
(arm/arm64/loongarch/riscv/mips/...) already handles single-PTE inserts;
they just now get more of them.

Boot-tested on QEMU sparc64 sun4u at PGCL=2 (PAGE_SIZE=32K, MMUPAGE=8K):
pgcl-stress now completes with Results: 12 passed, 0 failed where it
previously busy-looped indefinitely in the second-MMUPAGE write of
mt_mmap_worker.  PGCL=0/4/6 unchanged (PGCL=0 doesn't take this branch;
PGCL=4/6 already passed before this fix, presumably because the
larger-cluster fault patterns happen to populate the TSB via a path that
sidesteps the broken walk).
---
 mm/memory.c | 29 ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++-
 1 file changed, 28 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/mm/memory.c b/mm/memory.c
index e44414628898..c219394fcc64 100644
--- a/mm/memory.c
+++ b/mm/memory.c
@@ -4226,6 +4226,17 @@ static vm_fault_t wp_page_copy(struct vm_fault *vmf)
 				set_pte_at(mm, a, ptep,
 					   pte_mksub(base_entry,
 						     pte_suboffset(pteval)));
+				/*
+				 * Refresh the arch MMU cache for the neighbor
+				 * sub-PTE we just rewrote.  Without this the
+				 * faulting sub-PTE alone gets its entry above
+				 * via update_mmu_cache_range(..., 1) — the rest
+				 * rely on the TLB miss handler walking the page
+				 * tables for the new PTE, which on sparc64
+				 * PGCL=2 loops indefinitely after a COW write
+				 * to the second sub-MMUPAGE of a cluster.
+				 */
+				update_mmu_cache_range(vmf, vma, a, ptep, 1);
 				folio_remove_rmap_pte(old_folio,
 						      pte_page(pteval), vma);
 				extra++;
@@ -5943,6 +5954,20 @@ static vm_fault_t do_anonymous_page(struct vm_fault *vmf)
 			if (!pte_none(ptep_get(ptep)))
 				continue;
 			set_ptes(vma->vm_mm, a, ptep, pte_mksub(entry, (unsigned long)j * MMUPAGE_SIZE), 1);
+			/*
+			 * Pre-insert the per-sub-PTE arch MMU cache entry now,
+			 * not just for the faulting sub-PTE.  Without this the
+			 * remaining sub-PTEs in the cluster get inserted into
+			 * the arch cache only when the userspace next touches
+			 * them and the TLB miss handler walks the page tables;
+			 * on sparc64 PGCL=2 (4 MMUPAGEs per PAGE) that path
+			 * loops indefinitely instead of completing the TLB
+			 * fill, so the second sub-PAGE write traps forever.
+			 * Inserting eagerly here bypasses the broken slow walk
+			 * and matches how update_mmu_cache_range is normally
+			 * called paired with set_ptes for each installed PTE.
+			 */
+			update_mmu_cache_range(vmf, vma, a, ptep, 1);
 			rss++;
 		}
 		/*
@@ -5962,7 +5987,9 @@ static vm_fault_t do_anonymous_page(struct vm_fault *vmf)
 		}
 		/* Fix RSS: we added 1 above (nr_pages), need rss total */
 		add_mm_counter(vma->vm_mm, MM_ANONPAGES, rss - 1);
-		update_mmu_cache_range(vmf, vma, addr, vmf->pte, 1);
+		/* update_mmu_cache_range is now called per-sub-PTE inside the
+		 * loop above; no trailing call needed.
+		 */
 		goto unlock;
 	}
 #endif
